# Production / manual-QA stack env — copy to `.env` in this folder and fill in
# real values:
#   cp example.env .env
#   chmod 600 .env   # it holds secrets — keep it owner-readable only
#
# These keys are interpolated into docker-compose.yml. DB_MARIADB_URL, DB_POSTGRES_URL
# (the only two DB-connection env vars the app reads — see the app repo's
# CLAUDE.md, Environment section) and REDIS_URL are NOT here — they are
# hardcoded to the internal service names (mariadb-master / postgres / redis)
# inside the compose file; only the individual DB passwords below are
# parameterized. Which plane (domain/control) actually uses which provider at
# runtime is a choice made once in the Initial Configuration Wizard, not fixed
# by these env vars — see docker-compose.yml's comments.
#
# The app image is NOT configured here either: docker-compose.yml runs
# `ngmaibulat/usiem-tracker:latest`. Versioned tags (vX.Y.Z) exist in the
# registry for rollback — see the rollback section in DEPLOY.md.

# --- Required ---

# JWT signing secret + AES key for stored SMTP / DB-connection passwords.
# OPTIONAL: leave unset to use the strong secret the setup wizard generates and
# stores in the registry (recommended default). Set a non-blank value only to
# pin the key outside the registry file (e.g. via Docker secrets); it must then
# be strong — placeholders like "change-me" trigger a startup security error in
# production. Rotating the effective secret invalidates stored secrets and
# sessions. Generate e.g.: openssl rand -hex 32
# APP_SECRET=

# Public HTTPS origin, used to build invite/reset links in outbound emails.
# Behind nginx this is the external URL, e.g. https://siem.example.local
APP_URL=https://siem.example.local

# Fallback forecast target date (YYYY-MM-DD) when none is stored in the DB.
TARGET_DATE=2026-12-31

# Meilisearch master key — required because the service runs with
# MEILI_ENV=production, which refuses to start without a key of >= 16 bytes.
# Generate e.g.: openssl rand -base64 32
MEILI_MASTER_KEY=change-me-min-16-bytes

# --- Optional ---

# Postgres password for the internal `postgres` service (user `siem`; the
# wizard's default/intended assignment for the CONTROL plane in this topology —
# see docker-compose.yml). Defaults to `siem_password` when unset — fine while
# the DB is reachable only inside the compose network; set your own to harden.
# Interpolated into DB_POSTGRES_URL/RESTORE_PG_URL, so avoid characters that
# need URL-encoding (@ : / ? # %) or encode them. Changing it later does NOT
# update an already-initialized postgres volume — ALTER the role's password in
# the DB as well.
# POSTGRES_PASSWORD=

# MariaDB passwords for the internal mariadb-master/slave1/slave2 services
# (the wizard's default/intended assignment for the DOMAIN plane). All default
# to fixed placeholder values when unset — fine while reachable only inside
# the compose network; set your own to harden. Interpolated into
# DB_MARIADB_URL, so avoid characters that need URL-encoding (@ : / ? # %) or
# encode them. As with POSTGRES_PASSWORD, changing these later does NOT update
# an already-initialized mariadb volume.
#   MARIADB_ROOT_PASSWORD — root superuser, used by healthchecks and the
#     replication-wiring entrypoint on each node. Defaults to
#     `mariadb_root_password`.
#   MARIADB_PASSWORD — the app's `siem` user (auto-created + granted on
#     siem_source_tracker by the official mariadb image). Defaults to
#     `siem_password`.
#   MARIADB_REPL_PASSWORD — the `repl` replication account each slave
#     authenticates with against the master. Defaults to `repl_password`.
# MARIADB_ROOT_PASSWORD=
# MARIADB_PASSWORD=
# MARIADB_REPL_PASSWORD=

# Shared secret for the cron daily-snapshot endpoint (FR-14). Leave unset to
# disable the token path (the in-app ADMIN/MANAGER trigger still works).
# SNAPSHOT_TOKEN=

# Shared secret between the app and the external scheduler service (FR-46,
# scheduled report delivery — the `scheduler` compose service). Generate e.g.:
# openssl rand -hex 32. Leave unset to disable: the app's scheduler endpoints
# answer 503, and the scheduler container exits on start (comment the service
# out in docker-compose.yml to stop it respawning). The in-app "Run now"
# trigger at /admin/scheduler still works without it.
# SCHEDULER_TOKEN=

# MinIO root password — backs S3-compatible object storage for the rich-text
# editor's pasted-image uploads (S3_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY, docker-compose.yml).
# Defaults to `siem_minio_password` when unset — fine while reachable only
# inside the compose network; set your own to harden. Avoid characters that
# need URL-encoding (@ : / ? # %). Changing it later does NOT update an
# already-initialized minio_data volume.
# MINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD=

# Which plane (domain/control) uses which provider at RUNTIME is a wizard
# choice, stored in the connection registry, never re-derived from an env var
# (no plane can be silently overridden by the environment) — the app then
# migrates whatever it resolves there itself at every start (FR-47). Edit
# docker-compose.yml directly if you need a different default topology (e.g.
# control on a different/external server) offered to the wizard.

# No admin bootstrap: on a fresh install (no user accounts) the app boots into
# the Initial Configuration Wizard (/setup), where you create the first admin and
# set APP_URL / SMTP / the forecast target date / TLS artifacts. APP_SECRET is
# generated there automatically and used on every boot (set it here only to pin
# it explicitly).

# TLS_DIR / NGINX_CONF_DIR / NGINX_UPSTREAM / NGINX_LOG_DIR are NOT set here —
# docker-compose.yml pins them on the app service (/app/tls, /app/nginx,
# app:3000, /app/nginx-logs) so the wizard's generated nginx config + certs land
# on the volumes shared with the nginx container and the admin log viewer
# (/admin/logs) can tail nginx's access/error logs. On first boot nginx serves a bootstrap HTTP-only config (seeded by
# the app entrypoint); after the wizard finishes, apply the real config with:
#   docker compose exec nginx nginx -s reload

# HTTP_PROXY / HTTPS_PROXY / NO_PROXY / SQUID_LOG_DIR are also pinned on the app
# service: outbound HTTP/HTTPS (Telegram, health probes, npm update checks,
# holiday import) is routed through the internal `squid` service (FR-32) and its
# access log is tailed by the admin log viewer from the shared squid_logs volume
# (/app/squid-logs). The app degrades gracefully if squid is down.

# No SMTP_URL / MailHog here — this is the prod-shaped lab, so there's no fake
# mail catcher to prefill the wizard's SMTP step with. Configure a real SMTP
# server via the Initial Configuration Wizard or /admin/smtp; runtime mail
# config lives in the DB (SmtpServer rows), not in an env var.
